      <bioghist id="aspace_46eadffd71e19838d32db1841aa759da">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>The Harold Washington Library Center, Chicago Public Library's central building, is designed in the neo-classical style, using elements of both ancient Greek and Roman architecture. It was designed by Thomas Beeby, of the firm Hammond, Beeby and Babka, who won the 1998 competition conducted by the library. At the time of its opening, on October 7, 1991, the Harold Washington Library Center was the largest public library in the world, at 756,640 square feet.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_d902db3d605cacff61f282fe243969a8">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection consists of submission proposals and technical specifications from the five architectural firms that participated in the Harold Washington Library Center competition in Chicago in 1988. Also included are public comments and records of the Technical Review Committee.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
